{"title_page": "\"Shotgun\" Tom Kelly", "text_new": "{{Infobox presenter\n|name = \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly\n|alias = Bobby \"Shotgun\" McAllister\n|birthname = Thomas Joseph Irwin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/thomas_joseph_irwin_born_1949_3910536|title=Thomas Joseph Irwin, Born 08/08/1949 in California - CaliforniaBirthIndex.org|website=www.californiabirthindex.org}}</ref>\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|08|08}}\n|birth_place = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n|prevshow = ''San Diego Film Awards''\n|station = [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]]\n|image = \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly.jpg\n|caption = \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly in April 2010.\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|occupation = [[Radio personality]], [[television host]]\n|website = [http://www.shotguntomkelly.com Official website]}}\n\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n'''\"Shotgun\" Tom Kelly''' (August 8, 1949) is an American radio and television personality, two-time Emmy award winner, Billboard Air Personality of the Year winner and recipient of a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref>[http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/shotgun-tom-kelly Biography of \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly], LATimes.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nBorn in San Diego as '''Thomas Joseph Irwin''', Kelly worked  at [[KDEO]], [[KLNV|KPRI]], [[KGB-FM|KGB]], [[KCBQ]], [[KOGO (AM)|KOGO]], [[KBZS]] and [[KFBG (FM)|KFMB-FM]] before replacing the late [[Don Steele]] in the afternoon slot at [[Los Angeles]] oldies station [[KRTH-FM]], K-Earth 101. In August 2015, Kelly was taken off the air and became KRTH's \"Ambassador,\" doing personal appearances throughout Southern California. He eventually returned to the air as a weekend host.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/144804/shotgun-tom-kelly-segues-from-afternoons-to-k-eart ''Shotgun Tom Kelly Segues From Afternoons To K-EARTH/Los Angeles Ambassador''] ''All Access''</ref> Kelly exited KRTH in November 2016.<ref>[http://laradio.com/wherek.htm \"Where Are They Now?\"], LARadio.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref> In September 2018, Kelly debuts on [[SiriusXM Satellite Radio]]'s '60s On 6 channel.<ref>[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/179279 http://allaccess.com] August 21, 2018</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=February 2018}}\nThomas Joseph Irwin was born in [[San Diego, California]] at [[Scripps Mercy Hospital|Mercy Hospital]].<ref>[http://www.shotguntomkelly.com/about-me \"About Shotgun\"], ShotgunTomKelly.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref> He attended Our Lady of the Sacred Heart and Saint John of the Cross parochial schools for his elementary years. He attended [[Mount Miguel High School]] and was the announcer for the morning bulletin. In high school, he joined [[Junior Achievement]] which had a radio show on [[KOGO (AM)|KOGO]].{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nAt 10, his mother, La Von Irwin (n\u00e9e Driscoll), mentioned to Tom that there was a disc jockey doing a radio show in a shopping center in [[Lemon Grove, California]]. The disc jockey was Frank Thompson on KOGO-AM, who saw the young Tom Irwin looking through the window and interviewed him on the air. Following that experience, Tom became fascinated with radio shows, even putting together his own mock radio studio in his bedroom.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nA few years later, 13 year-old Tom went to other radio stations and watched the disc jockeys on the air. Tom visited Radio [[KDEO]] where he met program director \"Sunny Jim\" Price, who wanted to get a teenager's opinion of a song he was considering adding to the playlist. Price played the song for Tom, who liked it. The song was \"[[California Dreamin']]\" by [[The Mamas & The Papas]]. Radio KDEO was the first station in the country to play it. Price gave Tom his first job at a radio station helping with remote broadcasts.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Early career&nbsp;\u2013 1960s==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=February 2018}}\nIn 1966, at the age of 16, Tom was hired by Program Director George Manning to work on Sunday mornings at [[KLNV|KPRI-FM]] 106.5 in San Diego. Tom was playing  music sung by [[Frank Sinatra]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[Johnny Mathis]] and [[Sergio Mendes]] and [[Brazil 66]]. Every Sunday morning, he also did a children's radio show, \"The Uncle Tommy Show\", and played recordings from Disney Records. After high school, he attended the William B. Ogden Radio Operational Engineering school. He graduated in 1969 with his [[FCC]] First Class radio license and went to work at [[KYOS]] in [[Merced, California]].\n\n==1970s==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=February 2018}}\nAt 21, Tom worked at [[KACY]] in [[Port Hueneme, California]] using the name Bobby McAllister. There, he met DJ Dave Conley who named him Bobby \"Shotgun\" McAllister. Less than a year later, Tom and Dave moved to radio station [[KAFY]] in [[Bakersfield, California]]. Tom wanted to use his real name, but the general manager did not like the name Irwin, and asked Tom to change his last name on the air to Kelly. Dave Conley suggested the name \"Shotgun,\" from Bobby Shotgun McAllister, and they ended up using the name \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly. In addition to radio, Tom took a weekend job at television station [[KERO]], and did a television kid's show as NEMO the Clown.<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/shotguntomkelly/30290868475/in/photostream \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly as Nemo the Clown\"], flickr.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Tom was offered an opportunity to return to his hometown, [[San Diego, California]] when [[Charlie Van Dyke]] hired him at Boss Radio 136/[[KGB]]. Less than a year later, he was hired by Buzz Bennett to work at [[KCBQ]]. In 1972 Tom returned to 136/KGB.{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kv5KwAwtRxg|title=SHOTGUN TOM ON 136 KGB|date=January 26, 2009|work=YouTube}}\n\nShortly thereafter, he joined [http://www.440int.com/namesb1.html Buzz Bennett 440] for a job at [[KRIZ]] in Phoenix. He returned to San Diego and was on air weekday afternoons at [[KCBQ]]. It was while at KCBQ that Tom started wearing his trademark ranger hat.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac/10-questions/archive/17060/10-questions-with-shotgun-tom-kelly \"10 Questions with ... 'Shotgun' Tom Kelly\"], AllAccess.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nDuring this time, he was asked to host the kids' TV game show \"Words-A-Poppin\" airing on [[KGTV]] Channel 10 in San Diego, and syndicated to other cities. He won an Emmy for Words-A-Poppin' that same year.<ref name=\"lamesa\">[http://patch.com/california/lamesa/1976-spring-valley-s-own-shotgun-tom-kelly-wins-presi968e63e010 Spring Valley's Own 'Shotgun' Tom Kelly Wins Prestigious Billboard Magazine 1976 Award], Patch.com; accessed February 19, 2018.\n\nIn 1976, Shotgun Tom hosted a local television show in San Diego called, \"Disco 10\" which aired on KGTV. After local high school kids would go dance and take part in similar activities as they would on the more popular, nationally syndicated, \"American Bandstand\", the kids would then get to watch themselves on television at a later date.  The show aired on Saturdays at 12:30pm.\n\n</ref> In 1978, Tom won a second Emmy for Words-A-Poppin'.<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/shotguntomkelly/30590531946 \"Shotgun's Emmys and Billboard Award], flickr.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1976, Tom was hired by [[Bobby Rich]] to be the morning man at [[KFBG (FM)|KFMB-FM]], known as \"B-100\". Tom won the 1976 Billboard Magazine Air Personality of the Year Award and remained at B-100 for the next four years.<ref name=\"lamesa\"/>\n\n==1980s==\nWhile at B100, Kelly was offered a position at [[KUSI-TV]] as a booth announcer/on camera children's TV host with cartoons on The KUSI Kid's Club. He hosted the KUSI Kid's Club for 12 years.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-shotgun-tom-remembers-his-east-county-roots-2011feb21-story.html \"Shotgun Tom remembers his East County roots\"], ''San Diego Union-Tribune''; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn November 1987, Congressman [[Duncan L. Hunter|Duncan Hunter]] invited Tom to the White House to meet President [[Ronald Reagan]].<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/shotguntomkelly/9456466163/in/photostream \"With President Ronald Reagan and Congressman Duncan Hunter\"], flickr.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref> While visiting, Tom presented the President with one of his trademark ranger hats, which President Reagan donned for a photo op.<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/shotguntomkelly/9459246976/in/photostream \"With President Ronald Reagan\"], flickr.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1989 Mark Larson hired Tom at [[KFMB-AM]] to do a radio show from David Cohn's Corvette Diner in Hillcrest, and at The T-Bird Diner in [[Escondido, California|Escondido]].<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dR3IUM_4vtc|title=Shotgun Tom Kelly KFMB San Diego 1990 California Aircheck Video|date=August 10, 2010|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==1990s==\nIn 1993, Kelly was hired to work at [[KBZT]] K-Best-95 in San Diego. In September 1997, he was hired to succeed the late Real [[Don Steele]] and work in afternoon drive at [[KRTH]] K-Earth 101.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1997/RR-1997-09-19.pdf \"Ain't No Stoppin' Us Now\" (page 61)], ''Radio and Records'', September 19, 1997.</ref>\n\n==2000s==\nOn August 28, 2010, Kelly hosted the dedication of a monument at the former site of the [[KCBQ]] building and its six, 200-foot towers. The dedication was attended by over 400 of the radio station's fans and former on air personalities.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/80004/kcbq-a-remembered-with-monument-in-san-diego \"KCBQ-A Remembered With Monument In San Diego\"], AllAccess.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n \n==Television==\nKelly has appeared on several television stations since the early 1970s. In 1970, he took a weekend job at television station [[KERO]], [[Bakersfield]] to host a Saturday morning television kids show as NEMO the Clown. In 1972, Kelly was asked to host ''Words-A'Poppin<nowiki>'</nowiki>'', a game show for kids. The show aired in San Diego on [[KGTV]] Channel 10, and was also syndicated in several other cities. Kelly went on to win two [[Emmy Award]]s as host for the show.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2SnXjxnGJQo|title=Words-A-Poppin Part 1 of 3|date=April 23, 2008|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, Kelly was invited to host the [[Jerry Lewis]] [[MDA Telethon]]; he would serve as host of the telethon for more than 30 years. In 1982, he was offered a position at [[KUSI-TV]] as a booth announcer and on-camera host on The KUSI Kid's Club. Tom would continue as host of the show for 12 years. He has also served as station announcer for [[WFLX-TV]] FOX 29 in [[West Palm Beach, Florida]].{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Voice over==\nShotgun Tom's voice is featured in the motion picture ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]'', starring [[Denzel Washington]], and on ''[[America's Most Wanted]]'' and [[Spike TV]]'s ''[[1000 Ways to Die]]''.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nTom also did voice work for his hometown [[San Diego Chargers]]. Tom's voice could be heard on the [[Jumbotron]] during Chargers home games.<ref>[http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2015/aug/24/shotgun-tom-kelly-k-earth-101-radio-chargers-dj \"Radio won't be same without Shotgun Tom\"], ''San Diego Union Tribune''; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nKelly's voice is heard on [[Fred Falke]]'s song \"Radio Days\".<ref>[http://earmilk.com/2015/11/06/fred-falke-returns-with-radio-days-featuring-la-radio-icon-shotgun-tom-kelly Fred Falke returns with 'Radio Days' featuring LA radio icon Shotgun Tom Kelly\"], earmilk.com, November 6, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Hollywood Walk of Fame==\nOn April 30, 2013, \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly was honored with a Star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.<ref>[http://www.walkoffame.com/shotgun-tom-kelly \"Shotgun Tom Kelly on the Hollywood Walk of Fame\"], walkoffame.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref> His star is located adjacent to another K-Earth personality, The Real [[Don Steele]].<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H6hb3RgM55w|title=\"SHOTGUN TOM\" KELLY HONORED WITH HOLLYWOOD WALK OF FAME STAR|date=May 5, 2013|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://shotguntomkelly.com/ \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly's official website]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/ShotgunTom/ \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly's Facebook page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150905133435/http://kearth101.cbslocal.com/show/shotgun-tom-kelly/ KEARTH 101's Page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kelly, Shotgun Tom}}\n[[Category:American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:San Diego Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox presenter\n|name = \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly\n|alias = Bobby \"Shotgun\" McAllister\n|birthname = Thomas Joseph Irwin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/thomas_joseph_irwin_born_1949_3910536|title=Thomas Joseph Irwin, Born 08/08/1949 in California - CaliforniaBirthIndex.org|website=www.californiabirthindex.org}}</ref>\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|08|08}}\n|birth_place = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n|prevshow = ''San Diego Film Awards''\n|station = [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]]\n|image = \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly.jpg\n|caption = \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly in April 2010.\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|occupation = [[Radio personality]], [[television host]]\n|website = [http://www.shotguntomkelly.com Official website]}}\n\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n'''\"Shotgun\" Tom Kelly''' (August 8, 1949) is an American radio and television personality, two-time Emmy award winner, Billboard Air Personality of the Year winner and recipient of a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref>[http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/shotgun-tom-kelly Biography of \"Shotgun Tom\" Kelly], LATimes.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref>\n\nBorn in San Diego as '''Thomas Joseph Irwin''', Kelly worked  at [[KDEO]], [[KLNV|KPRI]], [[KGB-FM|KGB]], [[KCBQ]], [[KOGO (AM)|KOGO]], [[KBZS]] and [[KFMB-FM]] before replacing the late [[Don Steele]] in the afternoon slot at [[Los Angeles]] oldies station [[KRTH-FM]], K-Earth 101. In August 2015, Kelly was taken off the air and became KRTH's \"Ambassador,\" doing personal appearances throughout Southern California. He eventually returned to the air as a weekend host.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/144804/shotgun-tom-kelly-segues-from-afternoons-to-k-eart ''Shotgun Tom Kelly Segues From Afternoons To K-EARTH/Los Angeles Ambassador''] ''All Access''</ref> Kelly exited KRTH in November 2016.<ref>[http://laradio.com/wherek.htm \"Where Are They Now?\"], LARadio.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref> In September 2018, Kelly debuts on [[SiriusXM Satellite Radio]]'s '60s On 6 channel.<ref>[https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/179279 http://allaccess.com] August 21, 2018</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=February 2018}}\nThomas Joseph Irwin was born in [[San Diego, California]] at [[Scripps Mercy Hospital|Mercy Hospital]].<ref>[http://www.shotguntomkelly.com/about-me \"About Shotgun\"], ShotgunTomKelly.com; accessed February 19, 2018.</ref> He attended Our Lady of the Sacred Heart and Saint John of the Cross parochial schools for his elementary years. He attended [[Mount Miguel High School]] and was the announcer for the morning bulletin. In high school, he joined [[Junior Achievement]] which had a radio show on [[KOGO (AM)|KOGO]].{{citation needed|date=F